{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01PSLzJ7yaY361V3A37Dx9Ti","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# RNG Utopia - Capability Baseline\n     2→\n     3→Non-custodial P2P gaming platform on Solana. This document captures current implementation boundaries, architectural constraints, and planning direction without release labels.\n     4→\n     5→---\n     6→\n     7→## 1) Product Focus\n     8→\n     9→Current platform priorities:\n    10→- Real, playable game loops with on-chain settlement\n    11→- Verifiable fairness for completed rounds/matches\n    12→- Reliable wallet-authenticated flows\n    13→- Basic player history and operational safety controls\n    14→\n    15→This document is intentionally product-facing and avoids implementation-level details.\n    16→\n    17→---\n    18→\n    19→## 2) Current Capability Set\n    20→\n    21→### Core Platform Capabilities\n    22→- Wallet connection (normal Solana wallet flow)\n    23→- Non-custodial transaction flow for all financial actions\n    24→- Fairness verification experience for supported games\n    25→- Basic user profile/history views\n    26→- Operational controls (pause/resume, monitoring, incident response)\n    27→\n    28→### Not Implemented in Current Baseline\n    29→- Internal custodial balance model\n    30→- Multichain support\n    31→- Token utility and token-gated mechanics\n    32→- Referral and creator monetization systems\n    33→- Full social layer (global chat rewards, advanced social graph)\n    34→\n    35→### Planned Backlog Themes (Unscheduled)\n    36→- Chat and social features\n    37→- Reward loops and progression expansion\n    38→- Additional games and game variants\n    39→- Extended wallet and account UX\n    40→\n    41→---\n    42→\n    43→## 3) Architecture Direction (Locked)\n    44→\n    45→### Core Decisions\n    46→- Chain: Solana\n    47→- Custody: Non-custodial\n    48→- Program model: Standard Anchor programs (per-game + shared crate, see `docs/specs/004-shared-infrastructure/spec.md`)\n    49→- Wallet approach: normal wallets first, embedded wallet support evaluated later\n    50→\n    51→### Explicit Constraint\n    52→- Do not build temporary architecture with planned rewrite.\n    53→- Stay on a single architecture path: program-per-game + shared Rust crate (`solana/shared/`). See `docs/pivot-doc.md`.\n    54→\n    55→---\n    56→\n    57→## 4) Trust Boundaries\n    58→\n    59→### On-Chain Source of Truth\n    60→- All money movement\n    61→- Round settlement outcomes\n    62→- Payout eligibility and claim state\n    63→\n    64→### Off-Chain Responsibilities\n    65→- Read models and indexing for UX/performance\n    66→- Profile/history aggregation\n    67→- Backend-assisted fairness services (secret generation, partial-sign create flows, settlement workers, verification endpoints)\n    68→- Fairness presentation and verification UX\n    69→- Real-time coordination where needed for UX\n    70→\n    71→### Rule\n    72→- If it changes user funds or determines payouts, it must be validated on-chain.\n    73→\n    74→---\n    75→\n    76→## 5) Active Game Coverage\n    77→\n    78→### Lord of the RNGs\n    79→- Multiplayer tier participation with multiple entries per player\n    80→- Backend-assisted hybrid fairness (commitment at create, public entropy capture at spin/start, automatic settlement)\n    81→- Timeout-protected refund fallback\n    82→- Public verification payloads plus on-chain settlement evidence\n    83→\n    84→### Coinflip\n    85→- Match creation/join flow\n    86→- Backend-partially-signed create flow with wallet-authenticated requests\n    87→- Hybrid fairness outcome from revealed secret + future slot-hash entropy\n    88→- Automatic settlement with timeout-protected refund fallback\n    89→- Public verification payloads plus on-chain settlement evidence\n    90→\n    91→### Shared Game Requirements\n    92→- Idempotent action handling\n    93→- Replay protection for signed actions\n    94→- Clear error states for failed transactions\n    95→- Devnet-first validation before production rollout\n    96→\n    97→---\n    98→\n    99→## 6) Functional Baseline\n   100→\n   101→- Users can connect wallets and perform game actions\n   102→- All financial interactions are on-chain\n   103→- Coinflip and Lord of the RNGs are playable end-to-end\n   104→- Users can verify fairness for completed rounds/matches\n   105→- Users can view basic profile and recent history\n   106→- Operators can pause/resume games\n   107→\n   108→---\n   109→\n   110→## 7) Non-Functional Baseline\n   111→\n   112→- Reliability: stable under expected load\n   113→- Observability: errors and key events are visible\n   114→- Security baseline: rate limiting, validation, abuse protections\n   115→- UX baseline: clear transaction state feedback and recovery paths\n   116→- Operational readiness: incident checklist and rollback procedure\n   117→\n   118→---\n   119→\n   120→## 8) Workstreams\n   121→\n   122→### Workstream A: Core Game Reliability\n   123→- Keep Coinflip and Lord of the RNGs robust end-to-end\n   124→- Maintain fairness verification and settlement correctness\n   125→- Continue devnet and local lifecycle validation\n   126→\n   127→### Workstream B: Player Data and UX Hardening\n   128→- Improve profile/history accuracy and completeness\n   129→- Strengthen wallet and transaction UX\n   130→- Improve error handling and recovery paths\n   131→\n   132→### Workstream C: Operations and Safety\n   133→- Keep pause/resume and incident handling reliable\n   134→- Improve monitoring and alerting\n   135→- Maintain rollback and operator runbook quality\n   136→\n   137→---\n   138→\n   139→## 9) Readiness Checklist\n   140→\n   141→### Functional\n   142→- [ ] Wallet connection works across supported wallet paths\n   143→- [ ] Lord of the RNGs playable end-to-end with real settlement path\n   144→- [ ] Coinflip playable end-to-end with real settlement path\n   145→- [ ] Fairness verification works for Lord of the RNGs\n   146→- [ ] Fairness verification works for Coinflip\n   147→- [ ] Basic profile/history available and accurate\n   148→\n   149→### Security and Integrity\n   150→- [ ] On-chain payout invariants validated\n   151→- [ ] Idempotency and replay protections validated\n   152→- [ ] Critical abuse paths mitigated\n   153→- [ ] Emergency pause tested\n   154→\n   155→### Operational\n   156→- [ ] Monitoring and error reporting active\n   157→- [ ] Incident and rollback playbook documented\n   158→- [ ] Devnet soak tests completed\n   159→\n   160→---\n   161→\n   162→## 10) Risks and Mitigations\n   163→\n   164→### Risk: Uncontrolled feature expansion\n   165→- Mitigation: Require explicit decision records for major product shifts\n   166→\n   167→### Risk: Fairness complexity in multiplayer mechanics\n   168→- Mitigation: Keep acceptance checks explicit for entry weighting, winner selection, settlement, and public verification\n   169→\n   170→### Risk: Integration drift across docs and code\n   171→- Mitigation: Keep architecture and workflow defaults centralized in `docs/DECISIONS.md`, `docs/WORKFLOW.md`, and this baseline file\n   172→\n   173→### Risk: Wallet UX friction\n   174→- Mitigation: Prioritize stable normal wallet flows and clear transaction feedback\n   175→\n   176→---\n   177→\n   178→## 11) Success Metrics\n   179→\n   180→Primary:\n   181→- Successful completion rate of game rounds/matches\n   182→- Settlement correctness and claim success rate\n   183→- Fairness verification usage and pass rate\n   184→- Critical error rate within acceptable threshold\n   185→\n   186→Secondary:\n   187→- Early retention and repeat play behavior\n   188→- Time-to-complete for core game loops\n   189→\n   190→---\n   191→\n   192→## 12) Governance\n   193→\n   194→- Treat this document as the authoritative capability baseline.\n   195→- New features require explicit decision records before broad rollout.\n   196→- Architecture model changes require a dedicated decision memo.\n   197→\n   198→---\n   199→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8cdd94d4-4d50-4151-8136-428429db5806","uuid":"bc14a7f3-20d0-4816-bec7-4945850e8145","timestamp":"2026-03-25T15:25:09.930Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspaces/rng-utopia/docs/SCOPE.md","content":"# RNG Utopia - Capability Baseline\n\nNon-custodial P2P gaming platform on Solana. This document captures current implementation boundaries, architectural constraints, and planning direction without release labels.\n\n---\n\n## 1) Product Focus\n\nCurrent platform priorities:\n- Real, playable game loops with on-chain settlement\n- Verifiable fairness for completed rounds/matches\n- Reliable wallet-authenticated flows\n- Basic player history and operational safety controls\n\nThis document is intentionally product-facing and avoids implementation-level details.\n\n---\n\n## 2) Current Capability Set\n\n### Core Platform Capabilities\n- Wallet connection (normal Solana wallet flow)\n- Non-custodial transaction flow for all financial actions\n- Fairness verification experience for supported games\n- Basic user profile/history views\n- Operational controls (pause/resume, monitoring, incident response)\n\n### Not Implemented in Current Baseline\n- Internal custodial balance model\n- Multichain support\n- Token utility and token-gated mechanics\n- Referral and creator monetization systems\n- Full social layer (global chat rewards, advanced social graph)\n\n### Planned Backlog Themes (Unscheduled)\n- Chat and social features\n- Reward loops and progression expansion\n- Additional games and game variants\n- Extended wallet and account UX\n\n---\n\n## 3) Architecture Direction (Locked)\n\n### Core Decisions\n- Chain: Solana\n- Custody: Non-custodial\n- Program model: Standard Anchor programs (per-game + shared crate, see `docs/specs/004-shared-infrastructure/spec.md`)\n- Wallet approach: normal wallets first, embedded wallet support evaluated later\n\n### Explicit Constraint\n- Do not build temporary architecture with planned rewrite.\n- Stay on a single architecture path: program-per-game + shared Rust crate (`solana/shared/`). See `docs/pivot-doc.md`.\n\n---\n\n## 4) Trust Boundaries\n\n### On-Chain Source of Truth\n- All money movement\n- Round settlement outcomes\n- Payout eligibility and claim state\n\n### Off-Chain Responsibilities\n- Read models and indexing for UX/performance\n- Profile/history aggregation\n- Backend-assisted fairness services (secret generation, partial-sign create flows, settlement workers, verification endpoints)\n- Fairness presentation and verification UX\n- Real-time coordination where needed for UX\n\n### Rule\n- If it changes user funds or determines payouts, it must be validated on-chain.\n\n---\n\n## 5) Active Game Coverage\n\n### Lord of the RNGs\n- Multiplayer tier participation with multiple entries per player\n- Backend-assisted hybrid fairness (commitment at create, public entropy capture at spin/start, automatic settlement)\n- Timeout-protected refund fallback\n- Public verification payloads plus on-chain settlement evidence\n\n### Coinflip\n- Match creation/join flow\n- Backend-partially-signed create flow with wallet-authenticated requests\n- Hybrid fairness outcome from revealed secret + future slot-hash entropy\n- Automatic settlement with timeout-protected refund fallback\n- Public verification payloads plus on-chain settlement evidence\n\n### Shared Game Requirements\n- Idempotent action handling\n- Replay protection for signed actions\n- Clear error states for failed transactions\n- Devnet-first validation before production rollout\n\n---\n\n## 6) Functional Baseline\n\n- Users can connect wallets and perform game actions\n- All financial interactions are on-chain\n- Coinflip and Lord of the RNGs are playable end-to-end\n- Users can verify fairness for completed rounds/matches\n- Users can view basic profile and recent history\n- Operators can pause/resume games\n\n---\n\n## 7) Non-Functional Baseline\n\n- Reliability: stable under expected load\n- Observability: errors and key events are visible\n- Security baseline: rate limiting, validation, abuse protections\n- UX baseline: clear transaction state feedback and recovery paths\n- Operational readiness: incident checklist and rollback procedure\n\n---\n\n## 8) Workstreams\n\n### Workstream A: Core Game Reliability\n- Keep Coinflip and Lord of the RNGs robust end-to-end\n- Maintain fairness verification and settlement correctness\n- Continue devnet and local lifecycle validation\n\n### Workstream B: Player Data and UX Hardening\n- Improve profile/history accuracy and completeness\n- Strengthen wallet and transaction UX\n- Improve error handling and recovery paths\n\n### Workstream C: Operations and Safety\n- Keep pause/resume and incident handling reliable\n- Improve monitoring and alerting\n- Maintain rollback and operator runbook quality\n\n---\n\n## 9) Readiness Checklist\n\n### Functional\n- [ ] Wallet connection works across supported wallet paths\n- [ ] Lord of the RNGs playable end-to-end with real settlement path\n- [ ] Coinflip playable end-to-end with real settlement path\n- [ ] Fairness verification works for Lord of the RNGs\n- [ ] Fairness verification works for Coinflip\n- [ ] Basic profile/history available and accurate\n\n### Security and Integrity\n- [ ] On-chain payout invariants validated\n- [ ] Idempotency and replay protections validated\n- [ ] Critical abuse paths mitigated\n- [ ] Emergency pause tested\n\n### Operational\n- [ ] Monitoring and error reporting active\n- [ ] Incident and rollback playbook documented\n- [ ] Devnet soak tests completed\n\n---\n\n## 10) Risks and Mitigations\n\n### Risk: Uncontrolled feature expansion\n- Mitigation: Require explicit decision records for major product shifts\n\n### Risk: Fairness complexity in multiplayer mechanics\n- Mitigation: Keep acceptance checks explicit for entry weighting, winner selection, settlement, and public verification\n\n### Risk: Integration drift across docs and code\n- Mitigation: Keep architecture and workflow defaults centralized in `docs/DECISIONS.md`, `docs/WORKFLOW.md`, and this baseline file\n\n### Risk: Wallet UX friction\n- Mitigation: Prioritize stable normal wallet flows and clear transaction feedback\n\n---\n\n## 11) Success Metrics\n\nPrimary:\n- Successful completion rate of game rounds/matches\n- Settlement correctness and claim success rate\n- Fairness verification usage and pass rate\n- Critical error rate within acceptable threshold\n\nSecondary:\n- Early retention and repeat play behavior\n- Time-to-complete for core game loops\n\n---\n\n## 12) Governance\n\n- Treat this document as the authoritative capability baseline.\n- New features require explicit decision records before broad rollout.\n- Architecture model changes require a dedicated decision memo.\n\n---\n","numLines":199,"startLine":1,"totalLines":199}}}
