{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01RbPYRGg28CF87wEeEeqNbo","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have the full picture. Let me note:\n\n1. `REFERRAL_GAME_SETTLED` event type is defined in event-types.ts but NEVER emitted in the settlement flow (`recordReferralEarnings` doesn't emit it). It's only used in queue tests for testing the queue infrastructure itself.\n\n2. The claim handler validates payload at line 34-38, throwing an error for malformed payloads. But the question is: does the queue worker dead-letter on error, or retry? Let me check. Actually, the handler throws an error, and the queue worker will catch it and retry with exponential backoff. \n\nThe spec says malformed payloads should be dead-lettered, but throwing an error triggers retry behavior instead. After max attempts it gets marked as a permanent failure, which is effectively dead-lettering through exhaustion—acceptable but not exactly what the spec requires. I need to check if the worker differentiates between retryable and non-retryable errors to see if there's a way to force immediate dead-lettering for validation failures.\n\nLooking at the handler, it throws on malformed payloads, causing the queue worker to retry. But retrying won't fix a malformed payload—it'll fail the same way every time, wasting resources until max_attempts is exhausted. The spec calls for dead-lettering, which should skip retries entirely. This is a low-severity gap.\n\nNow I'm tallying up the criteria satisfaction across all requirements to compile the full gap analysis. Looking at the referral claim handler requirements more carefully, I'm verifying each acceptance criterion against the implementation. The event emission, idempotency checks, balance re-verification, and SOL transfer logic all check out, but there's a gap in how malformed payloads are handled—the handler retries them instead of dead-lettering them as specified. So FR-11 comes to 5/6 with that one missing piece.\n\nNow I'm tallying up all the criteria across the functional requirements to get a complete picture. Adding them up across FR-1 through FR-11, I'm at 90 total criteria, with 85 satisfied and 5 gaps identified. But I'm noticing the toast notification issue actually impacts two separate criteria—one in FR-9a and another in FR-9f—so that's a single implementation gap affecting two different requirements.\n\nLet me recount the gaps more carefully. I've got six distinct issues: the concurrent claims locking in FR-6, rate limiting on referral routes in FR-7, the toast notifications showing up as console warnings in both FR-9a and FR-9f, the missing game_settled event in FR-10, and the malformed payload handling in FR-11. That brings me to 84 satisfied criteria out of 90, with 6 gaps total. I should double-check FR-6 criterion 5 though—the spec details matter here.\n\nLooking at how concurrent claims are actually handled: the route checks the pending balance and creates a claim row, but there's no database-level lock protecting that balance snapshot. The handler does re-verify the balance before transferring, which means a second concurrent request could create a duplicate claim row even though only one would succeed at transfer time. Since the spec explicitly requires DB-level locking on the balance snapshot, this is a legitimate moderate gap—the prevention is only partial, happening at the handler level rather than at the database level where it should be.\n\nNow I'm moving on to document this gap and update the spec checklist.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6384,"cache_read_input_tokens":85379,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":6384},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8cdd94d4-4d50-4151-8136-428429db58